ity groups, the authors argue that the pandemic exacerbated existing inequalities in the UK, disproportionately affecting low-income neighbourhoods and Black, Asian and minority ethnic (BAME) communities. The book outlines recommendations in relation to developing a 'community-centred approach' in responding to future variants of COVID-19, as well as making suggestions for how to create post-pandemic neighbourhoods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBurnham, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillipson, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aYarker, Sophie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831111967940 cprintz978144736744440uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447367468?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447367468zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447367468/original  a978-3-11-119679-4 Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA